This PR mostly changes
```C++
if (property.name == "some_property" && some_condition) {
}

if (property.name == "some_property2" && some_condition) {
}
```
to
```C++
if (property.name == "some_property") {
	if (some_condition) {
	}
} else if (property.name == "some_property") {
	if (some_condition) {
	}
}
```
Basically when a property name is matched, there is no reason to check whether it has a different name (because it won't xd). 

Overall the way properties are checked in `_validate_property()` is not consistent. Some code was already using the latter style, some code was using `return` instead of `else if`, and some code was checking `some_condition` before the name. I did not adjust the style if the code was already avoiding redundant checks.

The new style is technically more performant, but that's not the main purpose of this PR. It's more for consistency.

On my readthrough of the post_import_plugin_skeleton_fixer.cpp I saw this for loop with i in place of j. I cannot think a reason we would need i but I may be wrong.

In case we do need i and not j, then maybe the for loop could be styled more like this:
for (const StringName &name : names) {
    path_string += "/" + name.operator String();
}

